The fathers taught their children, that GOD of his naturall goodnesse, wishing well to mankind, woulde have all men to come to the knowledge of the trueth, and to bee like in nature to God himelfe, holie, happie, and absolutely blessed. And therefore that God in the beginning, did create man to his owne similitude and likenesse, to the intent that hee should be good, holy, immortall, bles sed, and partaker of all the good giftes of God: but that man continued not in that dignitie and happie state, but by the meanes of the Divell, and his owne proper faulte, fell into sinne, miserie, and death, chaunging his like nesse to God, into the similitude of the divell. Moreover, that God here againe, as it were of fresh, began the worke of salvation, whereby mankind beeing restored and set free from all evill, might once againe be made like into God: and that he meant to bring this mightie, and divine woorke to passe, by a certaine middle meane, that is, by the worde incarnate. For as by this taking of flesh, he joyned man to God, so by dying in the fleshe, with sacrifice hee cleansed, sanetified, and delivered mankinde, and by givinge him his holie spirite, he made him like againe in nature to God, that is im mortall, and absolutely blessed. And last of all, hee worketh in us a willing indevour, aptly to resemhle the pro pertie, and conditions of him, to whose likenesse we are created, so that wee may be holie both bodie and soule. They added moreover, that the word should bee incarnate in his due time, and appointed age. And also, that there did remayne a greate daye for
judgement, wherein though all men
were gathered together, yet the righ
teous onelie shoulde receive that re
warde of heavenly immortalitle. So
the, this is the briefe summe of ye holy
Fathers tradition, which it is best to
untwist more largely, and to speake of
it more diligently, as it were by parts,
First therefore, the Fathers taught,
that the Father, the Sonne, and the
holy Ghost, are one God in the most
reverend Trinitie, the maker and go
vernour of heaven and earth, and all
thinges which are therein, by whom
man was made, and who for man did
make all thinges, and put all thinges
under mankinde, to minister unto him
things necessarie , as a loving father
and most bountifull Lord. Then they
taught that man consisted of soule and
bodie, and that he indeede was made
good according to the image and like
nesse of GOD, but that by his owne
fault, and egging forwarde of the de
vill, falling into sinne, he brought into
the worlde death and damnation, to
gether with a webbe of miseries, out
of which it cannot ridde it selfe: So
that nowe all the children of Adam,
even from Adam are borne the sonnes
of wrath and wretchednes. But, that
God whose mercie aboundeth accor
ding to his incomprehensible good
nesse, taking pitie on the miserie of
mankinde, did even of his meere
grace, graunt pardon for the offence,
and did laye the weight of the punish
ment upon his only sonne, to the intent
that he, when his heele was crushed
by the Serpent, might himselfe breake
the Serpentes heade. That is to say,
God doth make a promise of seede, that
is, of a Sonne, who taking flesh of a
peerelesse woman, I meane, that Vir
gine most worthy of commendations,
shoulde by his death, vanquish death
